reviews.review_text:
Best show of 1984 Can anyone find me a better show from '84? The band was absolutely flawless this evening (in as much as a Dead show can be flawless)! The happiness, the synergy, and the pure raw jamming power were in full-force this evening at the Cal Expo. A magical venue indeed. 

Each song is fantastically performed. Jerry is in rare form, Brent is key-clicking his toy piano, Phil's bass is big and loud; Bird Song, TLEO, Stranger, and even songs like My Brother Esau and Might as Well are especially hot.  

The sound quality is pristine. Enjoy this one!

5/5
Shaky show, with the downer of "Don't Need Love" to boot.
Brent! I love this show because njpg doesn't like Don't need love!!!! Spread some love my friends! so please.GIVE IT A WHIRL>Forever Grateful>Forever Dead

The second of two shows for me! Yep, it was on a sunday, the devil's day. I remember it was really windy! For about an hour. Then it settled down. After that, a really fine day with the dead in fine form. Phil  was just great.They had his bass turned up for a change. That song by Brent... "Don't Need Love" That one was strange. The crowd was buzzing in confusion. But all in all...they all sounded like Europe 72! They really did!
He's Gone! Totally agree that it is hard to find a better 84 show. Classic jam out of He's Gone

best show of 84???? The day before was much more inspired and killer!! 

Deal and Miracle-Bertha from the day before are epic!! This day was sloppy playing. I recorded it and recorded over my recording as I knew I didn't want to hear it again. 

Prolly one of the worst shows of 84. Jerry was wasted!
Awesome show for sure The sound quality is great and the band jams hard. I really dig this show.

rockin' A little sloppy in places, this one has the in the moment presence of an '84 show along with the speed of the following year.  The impatience of the band is evident when someone (drummer) yells at Bob to "start it" during the opening beats of BIODTL.  Even Birdsong rocks.  Most rockin': Might as Well, Truckin', NFA.  Jerry is very inventive with his note choices (and fret choices) throughout the evening, choosing unique combinations and inversions.
